 looks at the activities of four theatre groups or networks, focusing on their operating strategies and on close analyses of selected dramatic texts. She shows that while each group works under the rubric of Mayan or indigenous theatre, their works are also in constant dialogue, confrontation, and collaboration with the wider, non-Mayan world. Her observations thus reveal not only how theatre is an agent of cultural self-definition and community-building but also how theatre negotiates complex relations among indigenous communities in Mayan Mexico, state governments, and non-Mayan artists and researchers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMayan dramaxHistory and criticism. 0aTheaterzMexicozChiapasxHistoryy20th century. 0aTheaterzMexicozTabasco (State)xHistoryy20th century. 0aTheaterzMexicozYucatán (State)xHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70234940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797505423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292797505/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK